# Documentation Standards

## Doxygen Comments
- **Always use Doxygen-style comments** for all public APIs
- Document all classes, functions, parameters, and return values
- Use `@brief` for short descriptions
- Use `@param` for parameters
- Use `@return` for return values
- Use `@throw` or `@exception` for exceptions (though prefer std::expected)

## Comment Style
Use the following format for functions:

```cpp
/**
 * @brief Brief description of what the function does
 * 
 * Detailed description if needed, explaining the behavior,
 * preconditions, postconditions, and any special considerations.
 * 
 * @param param1 Description of first parameter
 * @param param2 Description of second parameter
 * @return Description of return value
 */
auto functionName(int param1, double param2) -> ReturnType;
```

For classes:

```cpp
/**
 * @brief Brief description of the class
 * 
 * Detailed description of the class purpose, usage patterns,
 * and any important notes about its behavior or lifecycle.
 */
class ClassName {
    // ...
};
```

## File Headers
Each source file should have a file-level comment:

```cpp
/**
 * @file filename.cpp
 * @brief Brief description of file contents
 * @author Author name (optional)
 * @date Creation date (optional)
 */
```

## Implementation Comments
- Use `//` for implementation details and inline comments
- Comment the "why" not the "what" - code should be self-documenting
- Explain complex algorithms, non-obvious optimizations, or workarounds
- Document any assumptions or preconditions in the implementation
